text=:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild%0a:Essential: {Category.LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild$:essential}%0a:Title: The Indian Accent in Media%0a:Author: sanjana_m%0a:Section: D%0a:Completed: 24.04.2021 - 19:05%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210505-020757-370890#%0a* [-04.05.2021 - 19:07-] || TA_lili marked as complete%0a#foxend 210505-020757-370890#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aThis article looks at one specific aspect of the Indian accent and how it is made fun of and used to perpetuate stereotypes.%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0ahttps://vm.tiktok.com/ZMeQuMuDd/%0a%0aIn this example, the pronunciations of the words “watermelon” and “passport” indicates that a characteristic of the accent is the non-usage of [r]. Throughout TikTok, TV shows, and in standup comedy, people who are portraying the Indian accent often use [ɾ], [ɽ], or [r] depending on the word. This would be considered as consonant substitution, which people are decrying as ungrammatical.%0a%0aThis TikTok, which is a criticism of Indian English, as well as others, are just some examples of this. In more mainstream media, the Indian accent, specifically the issues with the [r] sound are used for comedic purposes. For example, in the show Phineas and Ferb, the character Baljeet has a strong accent and is known to be the less social more studious character, following Indian stereotypes. In Jessie, the character Ravi (the Indian-American actor actual speaks Standardized English) has an accent and is often the awkward anti-social kid. The stereotype of Indians as show owners is portrayed with an Indian accent by an American actor who plays Apu. Many other shows, like the Big Bang Theory, which involves an Indian character who cannot talk to women, perpetuates these stereotypes as well. %0a%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_lili:)
